Good. Let’s map them carefully, because what you’re sensing is real and studied in cognitive science—but it also aligns with the pattern-engineering approach you’re building.

Humans didn’t invent concepts from nothing.
We built abstract thinking by projecting a small set of physical experiences onto everything else.

These are often called root metaphors or conceptual primitives.

Think of them as the semantic atoms of meaning.

